<br>
I do think that some people have a natural tendency to be attracted to people of the same sex.  BUT, I do believe it is as much an aborition as a person who is attracted to children.  The main difference being adults who consent to it are not being abused like a child victim of pedophilia.  But I do not think it is a natural behavior.<br>
<br>
Second, every person that I personally know that is gay, (and I have had the opportunity to work very closely with many gay individuals at work) including my cousin and the brother of my friend EVERY single one of them were sexually abused as children.   I heard a statistic (and unfortuately I cant recall where) anyway the stat was that 60% of gay individuals were molested as children.<br>
<br>
Just my 2 cents. -- Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67@religiousdebate60574>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Convicted Skeptic</span><br>  Posts: 117<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/14/03 4:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=69.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How does Jehovah's dislike of homosexuality affect your.</span><hr size=1> Human sexuality was explained to me as a spectrum in school and I have found no reason to disbelieve that theory.  It is very rare to find anyone who is 100% at either end of that spectrum and what we tend to be is attracted to whatever we are chemically and biologically oriented for.  Then enter socially acceptable behavior and social programming.  Over the basic layer of orientation lies the social programming we go through as we are raised in our various cultures.  Consequently, you see many more polarized stances on gender orientation.  Men are so steadfastly manly and male and masculine and the stigmata of homosexuality is so stern, that it is only those people who are so strongly oriented at the base level they can’t repress it who allow it to be expressed.  Women are less rigidly constrained socially so you see more hugging and kissing across their population with fewer raised eyebrows.  An actress can do same sex intimate scenes and guys cheer and no one questions the woman after when she says “I am straight, it was only acting” yet the reverse could never be true for a man.  In classical Greek culture there was not the same taboo that exists today and there was a more socially pervasive expression of homoeroticism than you find now.  This supports the idea that it is not so strong biologically as it is culturally.<br>
<br>
Would I let a homosexual watch my kids?  Only if they passed all the same tests I would subject anyone else too.<br>
<br>
Would I be upset if a gay man taught my kids?  Only if he were so indiscrete about it in a way that I would find objectionable if a straight person did.  (Kissing goodbye at the car when dropped off for school is fine, making out in the lunch room is not, I don’t care what your orientation is.  Having a picture on your desk of you and your family is fine, the latest spread in Undergear isn’t…except maybe in sex ed?)<br>
<br>
Would I vote for identical candidates politically?  I’d vote for the gay guy.<br>
<br>
Would I vote for one I shared views with over a straight one?  Every time.<br>
<br>
Would I leave a doctor if he were gay or a straight female?  Only if s/he were unqualified, I am not particularly concerned with who sees me naked, doctor or not.  If she needs to play ‘hello kitty’ between patients, that’s her concern not mine, so long as she washes her hands. <br>
<br>
Question for Candy:  You admit you have hang-ups over the orientation issue, I respect that you can admit that and I endorse your right to choose based on what you are comfortable with.  My question is, what values will you instill in your children regarding this and how would you handle it if you found out they were gay?  I ask this because you concede your difficulty and it may be that you are unable to change your own view, but your children are not set in stone yet and how you raise them will shape the world I am raising mine into.  I want that world to just not care either way if they are gay or black or short or republican.  (This same question applies to anyone who expressed discomfort over the orientation issue.)<br>
<br>
Respectfully,<br>
 <p>DBC67<br>
